    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1900-01-22T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1900-01-22T00:00:00-05:00" n="704"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d704">
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Hay</persName> to Messrs. <gloss
                            type="to">Norton &amp; Son</gloss>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1900-01-22">
                            <hi rend="italic">January 22, 1900</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Gentlemen</hi>: I have to acknowledge the receipt of your
                    letter of the 17th instant, inclosing copy of your former one of January 13, to
                    which you state you have received no reply.</p>
                <p>The Department answered your last-mentioned letter by its telegram of the 18th
                    instant, saying that the attitude of the British Government, so far as the
                    Department is advised, is that— <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p rend="flushleft">food stuffs with a hostile destination can be considered
                            contraband of war only if they are supplies for the enemy’s forces. It
                            is not sufficient that they are capable of being so used. It must be
                            shown that this was in fact their destination at the time of the
                            seizure.</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <p>While this answer is in its terms not so comprehensive as to cover all of your
                    questions in terms, yet, in view of the principle indicated, the Department does
                    not apprehend that further difficulties will arise. It is impracticable for the
                    Department to prescribe instructions in anticipation of all questions that might
                    arise, and that can only be dealt with when they arise in the light of all the
                    facts and circumstances attending them.</p>
                <p>I am, etc.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">John Hay.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
